473	\section{Learning from Next-State Signals: Unified RL Across Interaction Types}
474	\label{sec:rl}
475	
476	\textit{We convert next-state signals from heterogeneous interaction streams, including personal conversations, terminal interactions, GUI interactions, SWE tasks, and tool-call traces, into policy gradients.}
477	
478	
479	
480	
481	
482	
483	\subsection{Binary RL for Personal Agent}
484	\label{sec:binary_rl}
485	
486	\textit{Converting evaluative next-state signals into scalar process rewards.}
487	
488	\subsubsection{PRM Judge Construction via Majority Vote}
489	Given response $a_t$ and next state $s_{t+1}$, a judge model evaluates quality of $a_t$:
490	\begin{equation*}
491	    \text{PRM}(a_t,\, s_{t+1}) \;\rightarrow\; r \in \{+1,\,-1,\,0\}.
492	\end{equation*}
493	Specifically, the PRM judges each action based on the user's next response or the tool-call results. Tool-call results usually lead to a clear conclusion. The user's next response may contain signals of satisfaction or dissatisfaction. If there is no clear sign of the user's reaction, the model also makes an estimate based on the scenario, although users are encouraged to provide more explicit feedback.
494	For general agents, the judge reasons about whether the environment's feedback indicates progress toward the task goal.
495	We run $m$ independent queries and take majority vote $r_{\text{final}} = \text{MajorityVote}(r_1, \ldots, r_m).$
496	
497	
498	\subsubsection{RL Training Objective}
499	
500	By directly using the advantage $A_t = r_{\text{final}}$, the training objective is a standard PPO-style clipped surrogate with asymmetric bounds \citep{schulman2017proximal}:
501	\begin{equation}
502	\label{ppoloss}
503	    \rho_t = \frac{\pi_\theta(a_t \mid s_t)}{\pi_{\text{old}}(a_t \mid s_t)},\,\,
504	    \mathcal{L}_{\text{pg}} = -\mathbb{E}_t\!\left[\min\!\left(\rho_t A_t,\; \mathrm{clip}(\rho_t,\, 1-\varepsilon,\, 1+\varepsilon_{\text{high}}) \cdot A_t\right)\right],\,\, \mathcal{L} = \mathcal{L}_{\text{pg}} + \beta_{\text{KL}} \cdot \mathcal{L}_{\text{KL}},
505	\end{equation}
506	where $\varepsilon = 0.2$, $\varepsilon_{\text{high}} = 0.28$, $\beta_{\text{KL}} = 0.02$. Note that this is a real-time conversational setting, so there is no group structure available for standardization as in GRPO \citep{shao2024deepseekmath}.
507	
508	
509	
510	\subsection{Hindsight-Guided On-Policy Distillation (OPD) for Personal Agent}
511	\label{sec:opd}
512	
513	\textit{Converting directional next-state signals into token-level teacher supervision.}
514	
515	
516	
517	\subsubsection{Why Token-Level Supervision from Next-State Signals?}
518	
519	Binary RL reduces the entire information content of $s_{t+1}$ to a single scalar $r \in \{+1, -1, 0\}$.
520	Yet a user who writes ``you should have checked the file before editing it'' communicates far more: not just that the response was wrong, but \textit{which tokens} should have been different and \textit{how}.
521	This directive information is lost entirely by scalar rewards.
522	
523	OPD recovers this information by converting the next-state signal into a \textit{token-level} training signal.
524	The key insight is that if we augment the original prompt with a textual hint extracted from $s_{t+1}$, the same model produces a different token distribution, one that ``knows'' what the response should have been.
525	The per-token gap between this hint-enhanced distribution and the student distribution provides a directional advantage: positive at tokens the model should upweight, negative at tokens it should downweight.
526	This is fundamentally different from RLHF \citep{christiano2017deep, ziegler2019fine} (which uses scalar preference signals), DPO \citep{rafailov2023direct} (which requires paired preferences), and standard distillation (which requires a separate, stronger teacher model).
527	
528	
529	\subsubsection{Token-Level OPD}
530	
531	\paragraph{Step 1. Hindsight hint extraction.}
532	\begin{equation*}
533	    \text{Judge}(a_t,\, s_{t+1}) \;\rightarrow\; \bigl\{\text{score} \in \{+1,\,-1\},\; \text{hint} \in \mathcal{T}^*\bigr\}.
534	\end{equation*}
535	If \texttt{score = +1}, the judge produces a concise hint in \texttt{[HINT\_START]\ldots[HINT\_END]}.
536	We run $m$ parallel judge calls.
537	A critical design choice: we do \textit{not} use $s_{t+1}$ directly as the hint.
538	Raw next-state signals are often noisy, verbose, or contain irrelevant information (e.g., a user reply may include both a correction and an unrelated new question).
539	The judge model distills $s_{t+1}$ into a concise, actionable instruction that isolates the directive content, typically 1--3 sentences focusing on what the response should have done differently.
540	
541	\paragraph{Step 2. Hint selection and quality filtering.}
542	Among positive votes with hints $>$10 characters, select the longest (most informative).
543	If no valid hint exists, drop the sample entirely, this is deliberate.
544	OPD trades sample quantity for signal quality: only turns where the next-state signal carries a clear, extractable correction direction enter training.
545	This strict filtering is complementary to Binary RL, which accepts all scored turns: Binary RL provides broad coverage with coarse signal, while OPD provides targeted, high-resolution supervision on fewer samples.
546	
547	\paragraph{Step 3. Enhanced teacher construction.}
548	
549	The hint is appended to the last user message as \texttt{[user's hint / instruction]\textbackslash n\{hint\}}, creating an enhanced prompt $s_{\text{enhanced}} = s_t \;\oplus\; \text{hint}$, that the model ``would have seen'' if the user had provided the correction upfront.
550	
551	\paragraph{Step 4. Token-level advantage.}
552	The policy model is queried under $s_{\text{enhanced}}$ with the \textit{original response} $a_t$ as forced input, computing log-probabilities for each response token. Then we have the token-level advantage in on-policy distillation:
553	\begin{equation*}
554	    A_t = \log\pi_{\text{teacher}}(a_t \mid s_{\text{enhanced}}) - \log\pi_\theta(a_t \mid s_t).
555	\end{equation*}
556	$A_t > 0$: the teacher (knowing the hint) assigns higher probability to this token---the student should increase it.
557	$A_t < 0$: the teacher considers this token less appropriate given the hint---the student should decrease it.
558	Unlike scalar advantages that push all tokens in the same direction, this provides \textit{per-token directional} guidance: within a single response, some tokens may be reinforced while others are suppressed.
559	Training follows the same clipped surrogate as equation~(\ref{ppoloss}), but now the advantage carries far richer information per sample.
560	
561	
562	\subsection{Combine Binary and OPD Methods}
563	
564	\textit{Let us build on each other's strengths and offset each other's weaknesses.}
565	
566	\begin{table}[h]
567	\centering
568	\small
569	\caption{Comparison of different learning methods.}
570	\label{tab:method_comparison}
571	\begin{tabular}{@{}llll@{}}
572	\toprule
573	\textbf{Dimension} & \textbf{Binary RL} & \textbf{OPD} & \textbf{Combined} \\
574	\midrule
575	Signal type & Evaluative (good/bad) & Directional  & Evaluative + directional \\
576	Advantage & Sequence-level scalar & Token-level directional & Mixed sequence and token-level \\
577	Density & All scored turns & Hint-accepted turns only & All scored turns \\
578	Feedback type & User / environment  & Explicit corrections  & Both implicit and explicit feedback \\
579	Signal richness & 1 scalar per sample & 1 value per token & 1 value per token \\
580	\bottomrule
581	\end{tabular}
582	\end{table}
583	
584	
585	The binary and OPD methods are complementary, not competing.
586	Binary RL accepts every scored turn, requires no hint extraction, and works with any next-state signal, including terse, implicit reactions (a user simply re-asking a question) or structured environment outputs (exit codes, test verdicts).
587	OPD should be enabled additionally when the interaction stream is likely to carry rich directive content: users who give explicit corrections (``don't use that library'', ``check the file first''), or environments that produce detailed error traces (SWE diffs, compiler diagnostics).
588	In practice, we recommend running both simultaneously: Binary RL provides broad gradient coverage across all turns, while OPD provides high-resolution, per-token corrections on the subset of turns where directive signals are available.
589	
590	
591	Therefore, we propose combining these two complementary methods with a weighted loss function. Note that they share the same PPO loss, and only the advantage computation differs. Thus, we can directly use the following advantage:
592	\begin{equation*}
593	    A_t = w_{\text{binary}} \, r_{\text{final}} + w_{\text{opd}} \left( \log \pi_{\text{teacher}}(a_t \mid s_{\text{enhanced}}) - \log \pi_\theta(a_t \mid s_t) \right),
594	\end{equation*}
595	where $w_{\text{binary}} = w_{\text{opd}} = 1$ by default. In our experiments, we show that this approach achieves significant performance gains.
596	
597	
598	
599	
600	\subsection{Step-wise Reward for General Agentic RL}
601	\label{sec:stepreward}
602	
603	\textit{How to combine the outcome and process rewards?}
604	
605	
606	\subsubsection{Why Process Rewards Are Vital for Agentic Tasks}
607	\label{sec:prm_necessity}
608	
609	In long-horizon agentic tasks, outcome-only rewards provide gradient signal only at the terminal step, leaving the vast majority of turns unsupervised.
610	A PRM assigns a reward to each turn based on the next-state signal, providing dense credit assignment throughout the trajectory.
611	Recent work has provided strong empirical evidence for this. RLAnything~\citep{wang2026rlanything} demonstrates that integrating step-wise PRM signals with outcome rewards consistently outperforms outcome-only training across GUI agents, text-game agents, and coding tasks.
612	We build directly on this insight in \method{}: our PRM judges each turn using the live next-state signal as evidence, and we demonstrate empirically (\S\ref{sec:exp_general}) that this dense signal is helpful for long-horizon RL settings.
613	
614	
615	\subsubsection{Integrate Outcome and Process Rewards}
616	
617	Verifiable outcomes are standard supervision signals in RLVR settings. Following RLAnything \citep{wang2026rlanything}, we integrate outcome and process rewards by simply adding them together, using $o + \sum_{i=1}^m r_i / m$ as the reward for step $t$, where the $r_i$ are independently assigned by PRM$(a_t, s_{t+1})$.
618	Unlike GRPO, the presence of step-wise rewards makes it less straightforward to compute advantages. \citet{feng2025group} group similar states and perform standardization within each group. However, in real-world settings such as terminal agents, states are not easily clustered. Therefore, we directly group actions with the same step index, which we find effective in our empirical studies.
